JSX is a syntax extension for JavaScript that allows you to write HTML-like code in your 
JavaScript code. It stands for "JavaScript XML" and is used primarily with React to 
describe the user interface of a web application.

React me JSX ek syntax extension hai jo JavaScript ke saath HTML ki tarah code likhne ki 
anumati deta hai. Iska matlab "JavaScript XML" hota hai aur iska upyog pramukh roop se 
React ke saath ek web application ke upayogak interface ka varnan karne ke liye kiya jata hai.

JSX allows developers to write declarative code that is easier to read and understand 
than traditional JavaScript code that manipulates the DOM directly. JSX code is compiled 
by a tool like Babel into regular JavaScript code that can be executed by a web browser.

For example, in a React component, you might write something like:

 
import React from 'react';

function MyComponent(props) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Hello, {props.name}!</h1>
      <p>This is my first JSX code!</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;


In this example, the MyComponent function returns a JSX expression that describes the 
structure of a web page with a div element containing an h1 element and a p element. 
The curly braces inside the h1 element indicate that we want to interpolate the value of 
the props.name variable, which is passed into the component as a property.

Overall, JSX is a powerful tool for building web applications with React, allowing 
developers to write code that is both concise and expressive.

